/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (Maps of the Atlantic carried, for centuries, islands that did not exist. Tracing four such) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (phantom islands from their first appearance to their eventual deletion, this paper examines) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (why non-existent places proved so durable on the chart. I argue that the persistence of) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (phantom islands reveals the conservative logic of cartography, in which a feature once) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (printed acquires an authority that direct evidence of its absence struggles to overturn.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 556.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 542.0 Tm (It is easy to assume that maps record what explorers find. The history of phantom islands,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (places drawn and named on charts yet corresponding to nothing in the sea, shows the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (relationship running the other way: maps could also create the expectation of land and send) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (ships to look for it.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm (This paper follows four Atlantic phantoms from their origins to their removal, a process) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (that in some cases took three centuries. The question is not merely how they arose, which is) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm (often mundane, but why they were so hard to erase once established.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 412.0 Tm (Origins of the Phantoms) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 398.0 Tm (Phantom islands arose from ordinary errors. A bank of fog mistaken for a coast, a misjudged) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 384.0 Tm (distance, a low cloud on the horizon, or an iceberg far from home could all generate a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (sighting reported in good faith. A cartographer, receiving the report, had little choice but) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm (to record it.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm (Once recorded, an island acquired a name, a position, and sometimes a sketched outline, all) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm (of which lent it an air of established fact. Later mapmakers, copying from their) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm (predecessors as was the universal practice, reproduced it without question. The error) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (propagated not through fresh observation but through faithful copying.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 254.0 Tm (The Authority of the Printed Chart) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 240.0 Tm (The durability of phantom islands rests on an asymmetry of evidence. A single sighting) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 226.0 Tm (sufficed to place an island on the map, but removing it required something far harder: proof) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 212.0 Tm (of absence. A ship that failed to find an island had, in the logic of the time, perhaps) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (merely missed it in poor weather or sailed past in the dark.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm (An island once printed thus enjoyed a presumption of existence that no single negative) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (voyage could dislodge. Only the accumulation of many failed searches, often across) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm (generations, eventually shifted the burden of proof. The chart was conservative by nature,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (slow to add and slower still to subtract.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm () Tj
